[1
Date: Sat, 29 May 1999 01:37:25 -0600
From: Bob Jue <jue@otc.isu.edu>

We have been waiting for the state epidemiologist or the site investigating
team to report to you about the Idaho hantavirus case fatal for a female in
her 40s. I report what was informally discussed with the district health
department epidemiologist investigating the case.
The woman lived in a mobile home with her family (spouse and two older,
teenaged (?), children) who are not symptomatic and appear healthy. The
home is an older (>20years) mobile home which had "heavy" rodent
infestation. It is located on a pasture-like site with harborage for
rodents, grass, weeds, scattered junk surrounding the home. Two of 15
rodents (I believe all were deer mice) trapped as part of the investigation
were "positive" for hantavirus. The surviving family members were going to
attempt a cleanup of the home following CDC and health district guidelines.
Hopefully, a final, formal report will be forthcoming.
--
Bob Jue
Senior Environmental Health Specialist
Central District Health Department
Boise, ID
e-mail: rjue@phd4.state.id.us
